<subSubSection id="C36265517A57FFD1FFCBFD05FD82FC52" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC736DA7A57FFD1FFCBFD05FD82FC52" blockId="20.[96,697,710,1016]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
This species was first found near Barraga Bay on the &quot;Sapphire Coast&quot; of New South Wales, but has now been found near Sydney. The tightly packed iridescent scales on the flaps of the males are thought to resemble sapphires, hence the name 
<taxonomicName id="4C784D597A57FFD1FFCBFCA2FF0FFCD0" authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2017" box="[96,205,865,890]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sapphirus">
<emphasis id="B90CEAC87A57FFD1FFCBFCA2FF0FFCD0" box="[96,205,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">sapphirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. During courtship display the fan is rotated from side to side at irregular intervals at a low amplitude (only several degrees in either direction). Except for side-stepping, leg and pedipalp movement is not important to this display.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
